  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel framework titled 'Feedback-Driven, Semantically Valid Data Augmentation for Software Fault Prediction,' which enhances bug localization accuracy by intelligently generating realistic faulty code variants during training. The core innovation lies in combining model uncertainty estimation with historical bug pattern analysis to guide data augmentation in a semantically meaningful way. Traditional data augmentation in software analytics often relies on random or syntax-based transformations (e.g., variable renaming, statement reordering), which may produce invalid or unnatural code, thereby misleading the model. Our approach instead identifies code segments where the fault prediction model exhibits high uncertainty (e.g., low confidence, high entropy across bug likelihood scores) and cross-references these with repositories of known bug patterns (e.g., common anti-patterns from SARD, recurring fixes in Defects4J). For each uncertain code region, we apply controlled, semantics-preserving transformations that emulate real developer mistakes—such as off-by-one errors, null dereferences, incorrect loop conditions, or missing boundary checks—but only if the resulting code passes static analysis and compiles successfully. These augmented samples are then fed back into the training loop, with an adaptive weighting mechanism that prioritizes examples reducing both uncertainty and false negatives. A feedback controller monitors performance drift over time, enabling the system to detect and respond to temporal concept drift (e.g., new coding standards, framework updates) by refreshing the historical bug pattern database and recalibrating augmentation policies. This creates a closed-loop learning system where the model improves not just from more data, but from *smarter*, *contextually relevant* data. The expected impact includes significantly improved precision and recall in bug localization, especially for rare but critical fault types, and enhanced generalization across projects and development phases. By grounding augmentation in real-world failure modes and model introspection, this method advances the state-of-the-art beyond heuristic or blind augmentation techniques, offering a principled, interpretable, and scalable solution for industrial-grade software quality assurance tools.",
